nor_text ="""
 The quantity of textual data on the internet is growing exponentially, and it is very tough
task to obtain important and relevant information from it. An efficient and effective method is required
that provides a concise summary of an article. This can be achieved by the usage of automatic text
summarization. In this research, the authors suggested an efficient approach for text summarization
where an extractive summary is generated from an article. The methodology was modified by
integrating a normalized similarity matrix of both BM25+ and conventional TextRank algorithm,
which resulted in the improvised results. A graph is generated by taking the sentences in the article
as nodes and edge weights as the similarity score between two sentences. The maximum rank nodes
are selected, and the summary is extracted. Empirical evaluation of the proposed methodology was
analyzed and compared with baseline methods viz. the conventional TextRank algorithm, term
frequency–inverse document frequency (TF–IDF) cosine, longest common consequence (LCS), and
BM25+ by taking precision, recall, and F1 score as evaluation criteria. ROUGE-1, ROUGE-2, and
ROUGE-L scores were calculated for all the methods. The outcomes demonstrate that the proposed
method can efficiently summarize any article irrespective of the category it belongs to."""

POS TAGGING  \n \nPOS tagging is the first step in any NLP based application. \nTagging is a sort of category that may be described as the \ncomputerized assignment of description to the tokens. Here \nthe descriptor is known as ta g, which can also represent one \nof the component -of-speeches, semantic statistics and so on. \nNow, if we talk about Part -of-Speech (POS) tagging, then it \nmay be interpreted as a method of assigning parts of speech \nto the given word. It is generally called P OS tagging. In easy \nphrases, we can say that POS tagging is a venture of labelling \nevery phrase in a sentence with its appropriate label of \nspeech. We already know that elements of speech \nencompass nouns, verb, adverbs, adjectives, pronouns, \nconjunction an d their sub -categories. Taggers use various \ndata of the form: dictionaries, lexicons, rules, and so on. [2] \nMost of the POS tagging falls underneath Rule Base POS \ntagging, Stochastic POS tagging and Transformation based \ntagging. Tag set is a collection of tags used for a particular \ntask.  Every tagger will be given a standard tag set. The tag \nset may be coarse such as NN (Noun), VB (Verb), JJ \n(Adjective), RB (Adverb), IN (Preposition), and CC \n(Conjunction) and so on. PROPOSED APPROACH  \n \nInitially the text is extracted from a file, or it can be user \ninput too. All those sentences are separated by delimiter  ‘,’ \nand ‘.’. All these grouped texts are tagged with appropriate \nlabels may it be noun, verb or punctuation marks using POS \ntagging and NER with the help of spacy core models. They \nare stored in the form of tuples. All these tuples are passed to \nclause fu nction of NLP toolkit which extracts semantic role \ninfo (Subject, Object), syntactical info (type of noun, verb). \nAfter collecting all the parts of speech, the main work in \nforming a sentence is of chunking, it groups the words into \nmeaningful chunks. The main of chunking is to group into \nnoun phrases. We combine the parts of speech tags with \nregular expressions. It is done by tagging a noun with an \nadverb or adjective which are related to them. By trying out \nvarious combinations sentences in the form of qu estions are \nformed.  \n \n             \n    Fig 1 - Flowchart of proposed system.  \n \n7. #multi Document Summarization
pdf_dir = r"C:\Users\manis\OneDrive\Desktop\MINI_PROJECT\PDF"
Multi_Doc_text=""
for file_name in os.listdir(pdf_dir):
    # Check if the file is a PDF
    if file_name.endswith(".pdf"):
        # Create a PyPDF2 PdfFileReader object for the file
        pdf_file = open(os.path.join(pdf_dir, file_name), "rb")
        pdf_reader = PyPDF2.PdfReader(pdf_file)
        # Iterate through each page in the file and extract the text
        for page_num in range(len(pdf_reader.pages)):
            page = pdf_reader.pages[page_num]
            page_text = page.extract_text()
            # Concatenate the extracted text into the text variable
            Multi_Doc_text += page_text
        # Close the PDF file
        pdf_file.close()
Multi_Doc_text

' \nWrite about the four elements of Big Data in Detail. \nBig Data is a term used to describe the massive amounts of structured, semi-structured, and \nunstructured data that is generated by businesses, organizations, and individuals every day. This \ndata is so large that traditional data processing techniques cannot be used to analyze it, and new \nmethods and tools are needed. To understand Big Data, it is important to know the four key \nelements that define it: Volume, Velocity, Variety, and Veracity. \n1. Volume: \nThe first element of Big Data is Volume, which refers to the sheer amount of data that is \ngenerated every day. The volume of data is growing at an unprecedented rate, and this trend is \nexpected to continue in the future. Data can come from a variety of sources, including social \nmedia, sensors, mobile devices, and websites. The volume of data can range from a few gigabytes \nto several petabytes or even exabytes. \nTo process and analyze this massive amount of data, new tools and techniques have been \ndeveloped, including distributed storage systems, such as Hadoop, and cloud-based storage \nsolutions, such as Amazon S3. These technologies allow organizations to store and process large \namounts of data quickly and efficiently. \n2. Velocity: \nThe second element of Big Data is Velocity, which refers to the speed at which data is generated, \ncollected, and analyzed. Data is generated at an incredible rate, and it needs to be analyzed in \nreal-time to be useful. This is especially true for industries such as finance, healthcare, and \ntransportation, where decisions need to be made quickly based on real-time data. \nTo handle the velocity of data, new technologies have been developed, such as stream \nprocessing systems, such as Apache Kafka and Apache Flink. These systems allow data to be \nprocessed as it is generated, making it possible to analyze data in real-time and make decisions \nbased on that data. \n3. Variety: \nThe third element of Big Data is Variety, which refers to the different types of data that are \ngenerated every day. Data can be structured, semi-structured, or unstructured. Structured data is \norganized in a specific format, such as a spreadsheet or a database. Semi-structured data has \nsome structure but does not follow a specific format, such as social media posts or email \nmessages. Unstructured data has no structure and can include images, videos, audio, and text. \nTo handle the variety of data, new tools and techniques have been developed, such as NoSQL \ndatabases, which are designed to handle unstructured and semi-structured data. These databases \ncan store and process data in a variety of formats, making it easier to work with different types of \ndata. \n4. Veracity: The fourth element of Big Data is Veracity, which refers to the accuracy and reliability of the data. \nWith so much data being generated every day, it is important to ensure that the data is accurate \nand reliable. Hadoop \nis designed to run on commodity hardware, which makes it a cost-effective solution for Big Data \napplications. Here\'s a detailed overview of Hadoop and its main components: \n1. Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS): \nThe Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) is a distributed file system that stores data across \nmultiple nodes in a cluster. HDFS is designed to provide high throughput and fault tolerance, \nmaking it well-suited for Big Data applications. \nHDFS works by breaking up large files into smaller blocks and storing them across multiple nodes \nin the cluster. Each block is replicated multiple times for fault tolerance, ensuring that data is \navailable even if a node fails. \n2. MapReduce: \nMapReduce is a programming model that allows users to process large datasets in parallel. \nMapReduce works by breaking down a large data set into smaller chunks and processing them in \nparallel across multiple nodes in the cluster. \nMapReduce consists of two main phases: the Map phase and the Reduce phase. In the Map \nphase, data is processed and filtered, while in the Reduce phase, the processed data is combined \nand summarized. \n3. Hadoop Ecosystem: \nHadoop includes several other tools and components, such as Hive, Pig, and Spark, that provide \nadditional functionality for data processing and analysis. These tools allow users to perform \ncomplex data analysis tasks and extract insights from large datasets. \nHive is a data warehouse system that provides SQL-like query functionality for data stored in \nHadoop. Pig is a high-level platform for creating MapReduce programs, while Spark is an in-\nmemory computing engine that enables real-time data processing. \n4. Hadoop Applications: \nHadoop is well-suited for a variety of Big Data applications, including ETL (Extract, Transform, \nLoad) operations, data warehousing, and large-scale data processing. Hadoop is also commonly \nused for applications such as log processing, real-time analytics, and machine learning. \nIn conclusion, Apache Hadoop is a powerful Big Data technology that provides a scalable and \ncost-effective solution for storing and processing large volumes of data in a distributed \nenvironment. Hadoop includes several components, such as HDFS and MapReduce, that provide \nhigh throughput and fault tolerance, making it a popular choice for Big Data applications. \n \nWhat is Hadoop? Explain in detail with all its features \nHadoop is an open-source, distributed computing platform that is designed to store, process and \nanalyze large volumes of data in a distributed computing environment. It was developed by Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella in 2005 and is now maintained by the Apache Software \nFoundation. \nThe key features of Hadoop are: \n1. Distributed Computing: \nHadoop is designed to work on a cluster of computers, making it scalable and fault-tolerant. \nHadoop\'s distributed computing model distributes data and computation across many nodes in a \ncluster, which enables Hadoop to process large amounts of data in parallel. \n2. Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS): \nHDFS is a distributed file system that provides reliable and scalable data storage for Hadoop. It \nsplits large files into smaller chunks and distributes them across the nodes in a cluster. It also \nreplicates these chunks to provide fault tolerance and data durability. \n3. In a traditional row-oriented database, data for each record is stored \nas a row in a table, with each column representing a different attribute or field. In a column-\noriented database, on the other hand, data is stored as a set of columns, each representing a \nsingle attribute or field for all records in the table. Here\'s an example to illustrate this concept: \nSuppose you have a database that stores sales data for a large retail company. In a row-oriented \ndatabase, you might represent this data as a table with the following columns: Order ID, Customer \nName, Product ID , Product Name , Product Category , Quantity, Price, and Order Date . Each row in the table \nwould represent a single order, with values for each of these columns. \nIn a column-oriented database, the same data would be stored as a set of columns, each \nrepresenting a single attribute or field for all orders in the table. For example, you might have \ncolumns for Order ID, Customer Name , Product ID , Product Name , Product Category , Quantity, Price, and \nOrder Date . Each column would contain all of the values for that attribute for all orders in the \ntable. \nOne key advantage of a column-oriented database is that it can be more efficient for certain \ntypes of queries, particularly those that involve aggregations or calculations across large numbers \nof records. This is because each column is stored separately, allowing the database to read only \nthe columns that are needed for a particular query. In contrast, a row-oriented database may \nneed to read all columns for each record in order to perform a calculation or aggregation. \nFor example, suppose you want to calculate the total sales for each product category. In a \ncolumn-oriented database, you could read only the Product Category  and Price columns, \naggregating the prices for each category. In a row-oriented database, on the other hand, you \nwould need to read all columns for each record, filtering by category and aggregating the prices. \nOne popular example of a column-oriented database is Apache Cassandra, an open-source \nNoSQL database designed for scalability and high availability. Cassandra stores data in a column-\nfamily data model, where data is organized into column families and each column family is stored \nas a set of rows, with each row containing a set of columns.  \nDescribe how relationships are made in aggregate databases. \nIn aggregate databases, relationships between data are typically represented using references or \nembedding. \nReferences are used to represent a many-to-one or many-to-many relationship between two or \nmore collections. Here are \nsome of the distributed models in aggregate orientation: \n1. Sharded distributed model: In this model, the data is partitioned into multiple shards \nbased on a sharding key or a hash of the key. Each shard is stored on a separate node, \nand the nodes can be added or removed dynamically based on the load and storage \nrequirements. This model enables horizontal scalability and fault tolerance, but it may \nalso introduce performance issues due to cross-shard queries. \n2. Replicated distributed model: In this model, the data is replicated across multiple nodes \nto ensure high availability and fault tolerance. Each replica can be stored on a separate \nnode or on multiple nodes in a cluster. This model enables high availability and load \nbalancing, but it may also introduce consistency issues if the replicas are not \nsynchronized correctly. \n3. Hybrid distributed model: In this model, the data is partitioned into multiple shards and \neach shard is replicated across multiple nodes. This model combines the benefits of \nsharding and replication, enabling both horizontal scalability and high availability, but it \nmay also introduce complexity in managing the data partitioning and synchronization \nacross the nodes. \n4. Federated distributed model: In this model, the data is distributed across multiple \nindependent databases or nodes, and a federated query engine is used to query and \ncombine the results from the nodes. This model enables distributed querying and \nscalability, but it may also introduce latency and network overhead due to the \ncommunication between the nodes. \nOverall, the choice of distributed model will depend on the specific requirements and trade-offs \nof the application, such as performance, scalability, availability, fault tolerance, and data \nconsistency. \n \nExplain the following data distributed models - a) Master - slave replication and b) Peer- to - Peer \nreplication a) Master-Slave Replication: In the master-slave replication model, one node (the master) is \nresponsible for receiving write requests and updating the data, while other nodes (the slaves) \nreplicate the data from the master and can be used for read-only queries. When the master node \nreceives a write request, it applies the changes to its local copy of the data, and then sends the \nchanges to the slave nodes to update their copies. The slave nodes can be used for read-only \nqueries and can be scaled horizontally to handle more read traffic. This model provides data \nconsistency, high availability, and scalability for read operations, but it may introduce latency and \npotential data inconsistency during replication. \nb) Peer-to-Peer Replication: In the peer-to-peer replication model, all nodes have equal rights \nand can both read and write data. Each node maintains its own copy of the data, and changes are \npropagated asynchronously between the nodes. When a node receives a write request, it applies \nthe changes locally and then sends the changes to other nodes in the network to update their \ncopies. This model provides high availability, fault tolerance, and horizontal scalability, as each \nnode can be used for both read and write operations, and new nodes can be added or removed \ndynamically. However, this model may introduce potential data conflicts and inconsistency, as \nmultiple nodes can make conflicting updates to the data. To resolve conflicts, peer-to-peer \nreplication typically uses conflict resolution mechanisms, such as timestamps or versioning, to \nensure that the changes are applied in a consistent order across all nodes. \n \nDemonstrate Sharding and Replication strategies and Discuss various conflicts in Consistency. \nSharding and replication are two common strategies for distributing data across multiple nodes \nin a distributed database system. \nSharding involves partitioning the data into smaller subsets called shards and distributing them \nacross different nodes in the cluster based on a sharding key. Each node is responsible for storing \nand managing a subset of the data, and queries can be executed in parallel across multiple nodes \nto improve performance. Sharding can be used to horizontally scale a database system, as \nadditional nodes can be added to the cluster as the data grows. \nReplication involves creating multiple copies of the data and distributing them across different \nnodes in the cluster. Each copy is kept in sync using replication mechanisms, such as log-based \nreplication or snapshot replication. Replication can be used to improve availability and fault \ntolerance, as multiple nodes can be used to serve read and write requests. In the event of a node \nfailure, one of the replicas can be promoted to the new primary node to continue serving \nrequests. \nHowever, both sharding and replication can introduce conflicts in consistency, as data may be \nupdated concurrently on different nodes. Some common types of consistency conflicts include: \n1. Write conflicts: Occur when multiple nodes attempt to update the same data \nsimultaneously. This can lead to data inconsistency, as each node may end up with a \ndifferent version of the data. \n2. Read conflicts: Occur when a node reads data that has been updated on another node \nbut has not yet been propagated to the reading node. This can result in stale data being \nreturned to the user. 3. Lost updates: Occur when two nodes update the same data concurrently, but only one \nupdate is applied due to a race condition. This can lead to data loss, as one of the \nupdates may be discarded. \n4. Dirty reads: Occur when a node reads data that has been updated but has not yet been \ncommitted. This can result in inconsistent data being returned to the user. \nTo address consistency conflicts, distributed databases typically use concurrency control \nmechanisms, such as two-phase commit, multi-version concurrency control (MVCC), or conflict \nresolution techniques. These mechanisms ensure that concurrent transactions are executed in a \nserializable or serializable-equivalent manner, preventing conflicts and ensuring data consistency \nacross the system. \n \nExplain the following - a) Relaxing consistency and b) Version stamps \na) Relaxing Consistency: Relaxing consistency refers to the practice of allowing some degree of \ninconsistency in a distributed database system in exchange for improved performance, \navailability, and scalability. In a distributed system, ensuring strict consistency across all nodes \ncan be challenging and may lead to high latency and reduced throughput. By relaxing \nconsistency, distributed databases can achieve higher performance and availability by allowing \nfor temporary inconsistencies between nodes. \nThere are different levels of consistency that can be relaxed, such as eventual consistency, causal \nconsistency, and bounded staleness. Eventual consistency allows data to be updated on different \nnodes without immediately synchronizing them, but ensures that all nodes will eventually \nconverge to the same state. Causal consistency ensures that causally related events are ordered \nconsistently across nodes, but allows for some temporal inconsistency. Bounded staleness allows \nnodes to serve slightly stale data within a bounded time period, ensuring that all nodes \neventually catch up. \nb) Version Stamps: Version stamps are a technique used in distributed databases to manage \nconcurrent updates and ensure data consistency across nodes. A version stamp is a timestamp or \na version number that is associated with each update operation, indicating the order in which the \nupdates were applied. When a node receives an update request, it checks the version stamp to \nensure that the update is not based on stale data. If the version stamp is outdated, the node \nrejects the update and requests a new version of the data from another node. \nVersion stamps can be used to implement optimistic concurrency control, which allows multiple \ntransactions to operate on the same data concurrently while ensuring consistency. Optimistic \nconcurrency control assumes that conflicts are rare, and therefore allows transactions to proceed \nwithout acquiring locks. If two transactions try to update the same data concurrently, the \ndatabase system will detect the conflict based on the version stamps and resolve it using a \nconflict resolution mechanism, such as rolling back one of the transactions or merging the \nchanges. \nVersion stamps can also be used to implement multi-version concurrency control (MVCC), which \nallows multiple versions of the same data to coexist in the system. Each version is associated with \na unique version stamp, and transactions can read and write data based on the version they \nrequire. MVCC allows read transactions to proceed without acquiring locks, and ensures that \nwrite transactions do not interfere with each other.  \nGive a brief note on Cassandra and it working architecture in detail. \nCassandra is a distributed NoSQL database system that is designed for high scalability, fault-\ntolerance, and performance. In [152]:
def Sum_Pegasus_Model(text):
    tokenizer=PegasusTokenizer.from_pretrained("google/pegasus-large")
    model=PegasusForConditionalGeneration.from_pretrained("google/pegasus-large")
    tokens=tokenizer(text,truncation=True,padding="longest",return_tensors="pt")
    summary=model.generate(**tokens,max_length=512,num_beams=4,length_penalty=1.1)
    summarized_text=tokenizer.decode(summary[0],skip_special_tokens=True)
    return summarized_text

# Calculate coherence score
def coh_score(summary):
    sentences = sent_tokenize(summary)
    vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
    tfidf = vectorizer.fit_transform(sentences)
    cosine_sim = cosine_similarity(tfidf, tfidf)
    coherence_score = np.mean(cosine_sim)
    return coherence_score

def relevance_score(original_text,summary):
    relevant_words = set(original_text.lower().split()) & set(summary.lower().split())
    relevance_score = len(relevant_words) / len(set(original_text.lower().split()))
    return relevance_score

def sum_Bart_model(text):
    #loading the tokenizer from pre-trained model to tokenize the text
    Bart_tokenizer = BartTokenizer.from_pretrained('facebook/bart-large-cnn')
    #loading the pre-trained model to generate summary
    Bart_model = BartForConditionalGeneration.from_pretrained('facebook/bart-large-cnn')
    Bart_tokens=Bart_tokenizer.encode(text,truncation=True,return_tensors="pt")
    Bart_summary = Bart_model.generate(Bart_tokens,max_length=512,
    num_beams=4,
    length_penalty=1.1)
    #decoding the generated text
    Bart_summerized_text=Bart_tokenizer.decode(Bart_summary[0],skip_special_tokens=True)
    return Bart_summerized_text
